title: Dale Earnhardt Jr., Denny Hamlin, Matt Kenseth, Ryan Newman eliminated at Talladega
text:
TALLADEGA, Ala. — Another controversial finish determined the next round of the Chase for the Sprint Cup.
NASCAR’s final eight drivers — Joey Logano, who won the race under caution at Talladega Superspeedway, Carl Edwards, Jeff Gordon, Brad Keselowski, Kurt Busch, Martin Truex Jr., Kevin Harvick and Kyle Busch — were determined when a crash unfolded during a green-white-checkered Sunday.
Logano swept all three races in round two, leading Dale Earnhardt Jr. — who had to win to advance — on the final restart before the caution flag flew.
Harvick, who warned via radio his No. 4 Chevrolet was blowing up after earlier in the race worrying his engine was going to expire, then later reporting he thought he had a broken exhaust pipe, checked up on the final restart. Then, he moved back down the track and bumped another car, setting off a chain-reaction crash as cars crossed the start/finish line. That caused the field to be frozen under caution, giving the win to Logano and eliminating Earnhardt Jr., Denny Hamlin, Matt Kenseth and Ryan Newman.
WATCH: Final restart and wreck and Talladega
There were accusations from other drivers — including Hamlin, who was caught up in the wreck — after the race that Harvick intentionally set off the incident to help protect his standing in the points. Harvick, the defending series champion, was very close to the cut line and crew chief Rodney Childers had radioed him that he couldn't afford to fall back in the pack.
"The 4 caused a huge wreck," Hamlin said after emerging from the care center. "He was going to be out and knew he couldn’t go anywhere, so he just made a big wreck so everybody was locked in."
USA TODAY
Kevin Harvick's faltering car brings accusations over Talladega finish
It took NASCAR more than an hour to announce the official results after reviewing video of the finish and Harvick's move. NASCAR vice chairman Mike Helton told the media after emerging from the hauler where tape had been reviewed with other teams, said: "Obviously there are some teams that questioned what the 4 car did on a restart. But procedurally we haven't seen anything — so far — on the restart that is suspect. We believe that we have done everything procedurally correct so far and the 4 did nothing wrong."
Helton did not rule out reversing course in the coming days if evidence came to light. While he called Sunday's results official, NASCAR always reviews tape and releases 'official' results the day after a race, leaving the door open for further changes should they be needed.
Helton also pointed out NASCAR has not shied from making such calls. In 2013, during the race at Richmond International Speedway, it later was determined through radio chatter that Michael Waltrip Racing had conspired to fix the end of the race to ensure Martin Truex Jr. made the Chase. The Friday before the Chase began, Truex Jr. was a kicked out. Penalties and fines were levied.
NASCAR announced Tuesday it would attempt just one GWC in the interest of trying to give fans a race finish under green and trying to keep drivers safe in light of recent horrific crashes at restrictor-plate races.
ELIMINATED DRIVERS
Dale Earnhardt Jr. was eliminated from Sprint Cup title contention. Earnhardt, who qualified fifth and led 42 laps, seemed doomed early by a pit-road penalty. After serving his pass-thru penalty, Earnhardt worked his way back up through the mass of cars, but he finished second, not good enough after entering the race 11th of 12 eligible drivers.
"I couldn’t believe he (Logano) gave me the bottom," Earnhardt said of the final restart. "I thought ‘this is a gift.’ I would have won for sure. I’m fine with the new rule. Per the rules, we’re running second. I can live with that. We did everything we needed to do. … Another 100 yards I would have had the lead (on the last restart, before the green flew.) NASCAR makes the calls."
Denny Hamlin , who entered the race second in points, was foiled early by a faulty roof flap. He had to pit several times to allow his crew to work on securing it after the first application of tape failed. He was caught up in the wreck during the GWC finish. He climbed from his car, which had flames coming out from the undercarriage, and threw his driving gloves in disgust.
"We had a self-inflicted day," a disgusted Hamlin said. "It took us four times to get our roof fixed. I feel like I did everything I could possibly do to advance but you have one bad race in a three-race season and you're done. It's frustrating. I don't have anything positive to say right now."

You may also like these photo galleries: Replay Autoplay Show Thumbnails Show Captions Last Slide Next Slide Matt Kenseth , who was spun out by Logano at Kansas Speedway last weekend while leading the race, ran up front much of the day. He was in a must-win situation after entering Sunday’s race in the last of the four elimination spots. He radioed during the race “Tell that 22 (Logano), I'm gonna knock him out after the race, tell him to hide behind his daddy." Kenseth was running at the end, but still needed to work his way up to the front in the closing two laps. He didn’t get the chance, as he was involved in the final wreck.
"It was a pretty tough ending," Kenseth said. "The 4 (Harvick) knew he was blowing up (and held up his lane). It’s disappointing. It wasn’t really racing. It feels like we kinda lost control of the situation."
Ryan Newman , who finished second to Harvick in making the four-driver finale at Homestead-Miami Speedway last year, also was eliminated. He had finishes of 15th at Charlotte and 11th at Kansas and his 12th-place finish at Talladega was not enough to secure him a spot among the final eight drivers. There are no winless drivers remaining in the championship field.
OVERTIME: With five laps to go, Jamie McMurray’s engine expired, setting up a green-white-checkered finish. NASCAR ruled on Tuesday there would be just one attempt to end the race under green, in the interest of balancing a strong racing product for the fans and keeping its drivers safer by eliminating two-lap dashes to the finish in restrictor-plate races. The last time the Cup Series raced at a plate race — at Daytona in July — Austin Dillon's car went up into the catchfence in a horrifying crash. Dillon and five fans suffered minor injuries.
Logano, Earnhardt Jr., Brad Keselowski and Jeff Gordon led the field to green on the final restart after Greg Biffle, who stayed out on the final two major green-flag pit stops and was pushing his fuel limit hard, gave up the lead and came to pit road for fuel under caution as the rest of the field prepared for the GWC.

You may also like these photo galleries: Replay Autoplay Show Thumbnails Show Captions Last Slide Next Slide Jimmie Johnson spun into the grass as Harvick and Kyle Larson also made contact as the field came to the start/finish line on the restart and NASCAR said that GWC attempt didn’t count because the field hadn’t reached the start/finish line. This despite the fact the track’s green lights were on (the flagman was not displaying a flag).
"That's the game we play. It's sort of one attempt, if we decide we want it to be," Logano radioed.
On the next restart, there was a huge pileup behind the leaders and a caution flew. NASCAR had to review the tape to determine the finishing order and it took several minutes before they declared Logano the winner. He swept all three races in the second round.
COSTLY PENALTY: Earnhardt Jr. had perhaps the fastest car in Alabama on Sunday, but his pit crew made yet another costly mistake with 69 laps to go in the race. The pit crew jumped over the wall too soon on a two-tire pit stop, which caused Earnhardt to return to the pits for a pass-through penalty. Earnhardt resumed the race in 27th place. “How can we do this with stuff like that???” tweeted Earnhardt’s sister Kelley . “OMG. I know they are human but geez.”
Earnhardt quickly gave a pep talk to his team on the radio: “"Don't panic. Don't panic. Things will work out. ... Shake it off, man.” Earnhardt later came back to take the lead.
USA TODAY
Dale Earnhardt Jr. remembers father's final Cup win
FLAPPING HATCH: Here’s a new one, on lap 85, Denny Hamlin had to pit after his roof escape hatch started coming loose and flapping. Hamlin pitted for his crew to tape the hatch down, but the repair failed. Seven laps later, Hamlin had to pit again. The second pit stop left him temporarily in 39th place, two laps down.
UNUSUALLY CALM START: The clean start to the race — the first 131 laps ran without a caution — was the longest green-flag run to start a Talladega race since the entire 500 miles went caution-free in October 2002. It was also the longest green-flag run of the season, beating a 109-lap run in the June race at Dover International Speedway.
